Funcs"],"metadata":{"id":"c4rMp2mA-Gvy"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["For many types of operations, NumPy provides a convenient interface into just this kind of statically typed, compiled routine. This is known as a vectorized operation. This can be accomplished by simply performing an operation on the array, which will then be applied to each element. This vectorized approach is designed to push the loop into the compiled layer that underlies NumPy, leading to much faster execution.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"vzUvm104-z_o"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["\n","#Consider following loop based implementation to ind reciprocals for each element of an array\n","np.random.seed(0)\n","\n","def compute_reciprocals(values):\n","    output = np.empty(len(values))\n","    for i in range(len(values)):\n","        output[i] = 1.0 / values[i]\n","    return output\n","\n","big_array = np.random.randint(1, 100, size=1000000)\n","%timeit compute_reciprocals(big_array)"],"metadata":{"id":"OZiMeLAm_A70"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["x = np.arange(4)\n","print(\"x     =\", x)\n","print(\"x + 5 =\", x + 5)\n","print(\"x - 5 =\", x - 5)\n","print(\"x * 2 =\", x * 2)\n","print(\"x / 2 =\", x / 2)\n","print(\"x // 2 =\", x // 2)  # floor division\n","#some advanced arithmatic expression   -(x/2+1)^2\n","-(0.5*x + 1) ** 2"],"metadata":{"id":"israrvnt_DqZ"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Aggregates"],"metadata":{"id":"KMUoLLFv_GUO"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["\n","\n","x = np.arange(1, 6)\n","np.add.reduce(x)\n","\n","\n","np.multiply.reduce(x)\n","\n","\n","#note the difference in output with accumulate\n","np.add.accumulate(x)\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"gBrHsvOm_KwA"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Answer Following Questions : (You should either type the answer in separate text cell or code cell as per questoins asked)"],"metadata":{"id":"15cusFeZ_MPg"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["1 :- What are UFuncs in numpy?\n","\n","ans :- UFuncs means  universal funcation In NumPy, a UFunc is a function that works on NumPy arrays element-by-element.\n","\n","Instead of using loops, NumPy automatically applies the function to every element in the array. This makes calculations fast and easy.\n","They allow you to apply mathematical, logical, or arithmetic operations to entire arrays without writing loops. For example, functions like np.add(), np.subtract(), np.multiply(), and np.sqrt() automatically apply the operation to each value in the array. UFuncs are optimized for performance and support features like broadcasting, which allows operations between arrays of different shapes. Because of this, UFuncs make numerical computations simpler, faster, and more efficient when working with large datasets.\n","\n","example\n","\n","\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","arr = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4])\n","\n","print(np.sqrt(arr))\n","\n","np.add([1,2], [3,4])     # [4 6]\n","\n","np.subtract([5,6], [1,2]) # [4 4]\n","\n","np.multiply([2,3], [4,5]) # [8 15]\n","\n","np.divide([10,20], [2,5]) # [5. 4.]\n","\n","\n","\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"nrWe8Es-_Ob7"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["2 :- Which are various attributes of numy arrays object?\n","\n","ans :- The NumPy array object (ndarray) has several important attributes that give information about the array.\n","\n","Main Attributes of NumPy Array\n","\n","ndim\n","Returns the number of dimensions (axes) of the array.\n","Example: 1D, 2D, 3D, etc.\n","\n","shape\n","Returns the size of the array in each dimension.\n","Example: (2, 3) means 2 rows and 3 columns.\n","\n","size\n","Returns the total number of elements in the array.\n","\n","dtype\n","Tells the data type of elements in the array (int, float, etc.).\n","\n","itemsize\n","Returns the size (in bytes) of each element.\n","nbytes\n","Returns total bytes consumed by the array (size × itemsize).\n","\n","T\n","Returns the transpose of the array.\n"," example\n"," import numpy as np\n","\n","arr = np.array([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]])\n","\n","print(arr.ndim)      # 2\n","print(arr.shape)     # (2, 3)\n","print(arr.size)      # 6\n","print(arr.dtype)     # int\n","print(arr.itemsize)  # size in bytes\n","print(arr.nbytes)    # total bytes\n"],"metadata":{"id":"ddm88ffIALEe"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["3 :- If you have 3 dimentional array in numpy object Obj how to identify its size, type and dimentions ?\n","\n","ans :-\n","To find Dimensions\n","\n","*   Obj.ndim\n","\n","This returns the number of dimensions.\n","For a 3D array, it will return:\n","To find Size Total number of elements\n","\n","*   Obj.size\n","\n","To find Data Type\n","\n","*   Obj.dtype\n","m\n","\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"_UmgF-6mAlXe"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["4 :- Consider array object named Obj with dimentions 3*4*2 and you want to convert it to 4*6 shape exlpain how will you do it ? Show this using a code cell, taking an example of 3*4*2 np array of random int between 1 and 50.\n","\n","ANS:- Step 1: Check total elements\n","3×4×2=24\n","4×6=24\n","4×6=24\n","CODE\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","# Create 3x4x2 array with random integers between 1 and 50\n","Obj = np.random.randint(1, 51, size=(3, 4, 2))\n","\n","print(\"Original Shape:\", Obj.shape)\n","print(Obj)\n","\n","# Reshape to 4x6\n","new_Obj = Obj.reshape(4, 6)\n","\n","print(\"\\nReshaped to 4x6:\")\n","print(\"New Shape:\", new_Obj.shape)\n","print(new_Obj)\n","np.random.randint(1, 51, size=(3,4,2)) creates a 3D array.\n","\n","reshape(4,6) converts it into a 2D array.\n","\n","Total elements remain 24, so reshaping works correctly.\n","\n","Thus, we use Obj.reshape(4,6) to convert the array shape."],"metadata":{"id":"ZJbQ6uG3Bqgw"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["5 :- Consider above 4*6 array, sample 2*3 sub array from left bottom of this array store the result in varible named subObjCpy.\n","\n","ANS :- In a 4 × 6 array:\n","\n","Bottom → last 2 rows → rows 2 and 3\n","\n","Left → first 3 columns → columns 0, 1, 2\n","So slicing will be:\n","subObjCpy = new_Obj[2:4, 0:3]\n","EXAMPLE\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","# Create 3x4x2 array\n","Obj = np.random.randint(1, 51, size=(3, 4, 2))\n","\n","# Reshape to 4x6\n","new_Obj = Obj.reshape(4, 6)\n","\n","print(\"4x6 Array:\\n\", new_Obj)\n","\n","# Extract 2x3 sub-array from left bottom\n","subObjCpy = new_Obj[2:4, 0:3]\n","\n","print(\"\\n2x3 Sub Array (Left Bottom):\\n\", subObjCpy)\n","2:4 → selects last 2 rows\n","\n","0:3 → selects first 3 columns\n","\n","Result is a 2 × 3 sub-array stored in subObjCpy"],"metadata":{"id":"Bbq4bY9fBuEg"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[" 6 :- Make changes in 1 perticular value in the subObjCpy. Check values of Obj subObjCpy to check impact of this change of element in original and copied object. What do you conclude?\n","  ANS :-\n","\n","  import numpy as np\n","\n","# Create original array\n","Obj = np.random.randint(1, 51, size=(3, 4, 2))\n","new_Obj = Obj.reshape(4, 6)\n","\n","# Take 2x3 sub-array (left bottom)\n","subObjCpy = new_Obj[2:4, 0:3]\n","\n","print(\"Original 4x6 Array:\\n\", new_Obj)\n","print(\"\\nSub Array Before Change:\\n\", subObjCpy)\n","\n","# Change one value in subObjCpy\n","subObjCpy[0, 0] = 999\n","\n","print(\"\\nSub Array After Change:\\n\", subObjCpy)\n","print(\"\\nOriginal Array After Change:\\n\", new_Obj)\n","After changing one element in subObjCpy, the corresponding value in the original array new_Obj also changes.\n","\n","This happens because slicing in NumPy does not create a copy, it creates a view of the original array.\n","\n","Hence, any modification in the sliced array affects the original array."],"metadata":{"id":"QjlXrg4gC_Yh"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["7 : - If you were to filter sub array view from above Obj object and want to apply modification in original and/or sub obj change respective element in other how will you achieve it?\n"," ANS:-\n"," In NumPy:\n","\n","Slicing → creates a view (changes affect original)\n","\n",".copy() → creates a separate copy (changes do NOT affect original)\n","\n","# Sub-array as view (default slicing)\n","subObj = new_Obj[2:4, 0:3]\n","\n","# Modify sub-array\n","subObj[0, 0] = 555\n","\n","print(new_Obj)   # Original array also changes\n","To apply modifications in both original and sub-array, use slicing (view).\n","If independent modification is required, use the .copy() method."],"metadata":{"id":"OkWfEjMfDTKc"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Conclusion : Thus we have learned basics of Numpy library for storing and efficiently processing any external data into python execution pipeline."],"metadata":{"id":"cjbuXXxiDi92"}}]}